<?xml version="1.0"?><collection name="D0838-B"><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>&quot;I pay extra attention when I'm talking on the phone.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>I don't know if they're going to stop for a cell phone when they're going to a robbery in progress.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>When one of them drives away with a door open and a baby in the back, you know there is a problem.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>&quot;To address the issue of distracted driving, you really should look at the totality of the issue and not just look at one behavior because a lot of people do it.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>But what are you willing to give up to do something about it?<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="29"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>Eleven states and the District of Columbia have put limits on teens using cell phones while they drive.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>Studies by the insurance institute showed that hand-held phone use in Washington decreased from 6.1 percent of drivers to 3.5 percent right after the new law went into effect, Rader said.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="4" sums="25,37,51,6"><scu uid="27" label="Effectiveness is difficult to assess." weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>It's difficult to identify a driver using a hands-free phone.&quot;<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="41"><scu uid="28" label="Enforcement is difficult." weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0094"><line>Opponents had a wide range of arguments.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051205.0960"><line>A first and second offense will carry a fine of between US$25-US$100 (euro21-euro85), while those guilty of a third offense could lose their driver's license for up to a year, police spokesman Sgt. Thomas Hannah said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>Police have no data on whether the D.C. law has reduced the number of accidents.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>A pilot study in 2001 found that cell-phone use in California was the No. 1 culprit in crashes in which driver distraction was cited as the cause.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>Use the technology.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>The driver stopped.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0173"><line>But it has been shown that hands-free phones are just as hazardous.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>Anecdotal evidence is also sketchy.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>The Legislature has twice come within a vote of doing the right thing.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0071"><line>At Fort Sam Houston, 56 citations have been given over the past four months, post spokesman Phil Reidinger said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>Some traffic-safety experts say the safety board's proposal is well-intentioned, but they question its effectiveness.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>&quot;We've always said it can be a potential distraction,&quot; said John Walls, a spokesman for CTIA The Wireless Association, the trade association representing such wireless carriers as Cingular and Verizon as well as phone makers and other industry-related companies.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>&quot;There's really no need to talk and drive.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>&quot;Sometimes an officer uses discretion.</line><line>Last year, D.C. police officers issued 6,018 tickets for driving with a hand-held cell phone, said Lt. Byron Hope of the Traffic Safety and Special Enforcement Branch.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="6"><scu uid="28" label="Enforcement is difficult." weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050806.0640"><line>It is difficult to assess the effectiveness of cell phone bans because a lot of laws rely on drivers or witnesses to confirm they were talking on the phone when they had an accident.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="22,42,49"><scu uid="27" label="Effectiveness is difficult to assess." weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>Since the day that maniac Paul Revere roared through the city's narrow streets at midnight, we Bostonians have considered bad driving a birthright.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>Let's look at banning radios.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>From the cabby's perspective, chatting up the passenger could be a good thing, leading to a bigger tip, he said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0094"><line>&quot;They completely gutted it,&quot; Federal Way Democratic Sen. Tracey Eide said Wednesday.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>He said officers ticket people all the time.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>Both parties, drivers as well as passengers, &quot;often feel like the other one's not treating them as a person,&quot; said Bruce Schaller, a transportation consultant specializing in the taxi industry.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0173"><line>But when one of those tasks is piloting a ton of steel, or more, at 100 feet per second, public safety requires a focus on that task alone.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>He was not badly hurt.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>Plenty of studies have confirmed the obvious.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>Tow truck operators said they have seen no difference in accidents.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>Here are three ideas we should consider:</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>No one was hurt in the July 2004 crash in Overland Park.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051205.0960"><line>Drivers caught using hand-held phones on the road will be fined under a new law aimed at reducing auto accidents in the U.S. Virgin Islands, officials said Monday.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="4" sums="11,20,25,51"><scu uid="33" label="Some places prohibit use of hand-held phones while driving." weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0094"><line>Eide was upset.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>&quot;We think that laws banning both types of cell-phone use while driving are probably a good idea, but the big problem with that is how do you enforce it?<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="36"><scu uid="28" label="Enforcement is difficult." weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>But in New York, he said, similar studies showed that hand-held use returned to old levels after an initial drop.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0094"><line>Eide thought this would be the year because most of the telecom companies dropped their opposition to the bill.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>The findings suggest that laws banning handheld cell phones give drivers a false sense of security and that perhaps it's time to consider an all-out prohibition on talking behind the wheel, according to the nonprofit Insurance Institute for Highway Safety, which released the report and noted that it is the first to quantify the injury risk of cell phones and driving.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="5" sums="16,23,3,33,35"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0071"><line>Randolph Air Force Base also is studying a cell phone restriction.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="13"><scu uid="29" label="Cell phone use while driving is being banned on military bases" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>A recent study by the insurance institute said drivers who use any cell phones were four times more likely to get into crashes serious enough to cause injury.</line><line>&quot;I think we give up a certain amount of autonomy to the machines we use -- they govern us rather than vice versa,&quot; she said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>What are you willing to give up to make the highways safer?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0173"><line>Increasingly, Americans are making multitasking a way of life.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>The study by the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration reported that the percentage of drivers between the ages of 16 and 24 who talked on handheld cell phones increased from 3 percent in 2002 to 8 percent last year.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="41"/></line><line>He was among a group of teens enrolled in a driver's education class at Olathe South School who recently shared their views about driving and talking on cell phones.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0094"><line>It passed the state Senate but ran into fierce opposition in the House.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0071"><line>Hands-free devices don't fully prevent accidents, because they allow motorists to have a conversation when they should focus on driving, he said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>Matthew W. Daus, the taxi commissioner, calls the cell phone problem &quot;a challenging enforcement issue&quot; because it is not easy for an inspector standing on the street to tell if a driver is on a hands-free phone.</line><line>(Remember when the Giuliani administration, ever graceful, called them &quot;taxi terrorists&quot; for daring to protest city policies they considered unfair?)</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>This is hardly radical stuff: In 1910, Massachusetts once used a device known as a photo speed recorder, and its use was upheld by the Supreme Judicial Court.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>Mom, first name Maggie, went through her usual taxi routine of buckling Max in, car seat and all, and putting the frame of the stroller in the trunk.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>Everyone knows wearing a seat belt is the right thing to do.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0173"><line>They have proven to be a dangerous distraction.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>&quot;Young drivers face a lot of potential distractions, from playing their music too loudly to other kids in the car to talking on a cell phone to eating.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0173"><line>A Harvard study estimates that 6 percent of US accidents, and 2,600 deaths a year, are linked to cellphones.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>But lawmakers who lead transportation committees in Missouri and Kansas said they did not think cell-phone restrictions for teens would advance in their states.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050806.0640"><line>On the Net:</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>About a third involved a dr iver who was younger than 21.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>But hands free is not risk free.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0173"><line>BICYCLISTS SAY THESE motorists are indistinguishable from drunk drivers.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>&quot;Everybody does it,&quot; said Ann Edwards, a retiree who lives on Capitol Hill, &quot;and I think it's dangerous.&quot;<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="0"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>That it is.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>At the same time, cell phones increasingly contribute to crashes in Kansas and Missouri among drivers younger than 21.</line><line>Some teens recognize the risk, but others discount the danger that cell phones might pose.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>&quot;This is a distraction that tends to last over a period of time,&quot; Rader said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>She said she understood the gravity of driving.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="12,32"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0173"><line>They - it will come as no surprise - are drivers using cellphones.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>Running red lights is the leading cause of urban accidents, according to the National Conference of State Legislatures, causing more than 200,000 crashes and 900 deaths every year.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0071"><line>The restrictions followed a study by the National<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="13,43"/></line><line>After a 60-day grace period, military personnel, government employees and civilian visitors could be banned from driving on Lackland for up to a year if they're cited for violating the rule four times over the course of 12 months.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>As she talked on her cell phone, a 17-year-old girl drove over a curb and through a field before striking a tree last May in Overland Park.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>But for every driver silenced with a $100 fine, many others are still out there talking on hand-held phones, casually disregarding the law.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="25,48,51"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>The institute conducted the study in Western Australia because it said U.S. phone companies would not allow its researchers access to personal phone records.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>&quot;I'd rather have all my concentration so I don't hit someone.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0094"><line>Eide's bill would have outlawed talking on a cell phone while driving unless drivers were using headsets or other hands-free devices.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="37,49,6"><scu uid="33" label="Some places prohibit use of hand-held phones while driving." weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>Still, she has a problem with a government ban.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>&quot;It's almost like a useless law to a certain extent,&quot; Williams said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050806.0640"><line>&quot;For lawmakers, it's a foot in the door,&quot; said Matt Sundeen, a policy researcher with the legislatures group.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>Researchers also wanted to test the risks in that area of Australia where there has been a ban on using handheld devices.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0094"><line>&quot;The problem with her bill is that it picks out one piece of technology,&quot; Morris said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>Police began enforcing the law in August 2004.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="10,13"/></line><line>The emphasis on cell phones also discounts other activities that take people's eyes and minds off the road.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>This is not an exercise in cabby-bashing.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0173"><line>And mature drivers who are not paying attention can be as dangerous as young ones.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050806.0640"><line>Bills were passed or are still being considered in 22 states, according to the National Conference of State Legislatures in Denver.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="29,8"><scu uid="26" label="States have tried to pass restrictive cellphone/driving legislation" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>It's the law that nearly everyone supports -- and nearly everyone ignores.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>With this technology they can ease their isolation.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0173"><line>A bill has been filed in Massachusetts that would outlaw only the use of hand-held phones, and another that would apply only to young drivers.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>At least 11 other states have considered such laws, including Michigan, which is poised to ban cell-phone use by drivers younger than 18.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="44"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0094"><line>A proposal in Olympia to ban driving while talking on hand-held cell phones crashed in the state House.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="9" sums="10,11,14,23,25,41,44,51,6"><scu uid="26" label="States have tried to pass restrictive cellphone/driving legislation" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0173"><line>Regular drivers watch for their last-minute swerves down a side street or onto an exit ramp.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>He can be reached at baileyglobe.com or at 617-929-2902.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>&quot;People are going to do it.&quot;<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>How's that for a parent's nightmare?<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>The privacy issue is a red herring; people simply don't like tickets.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>Staff writer Rosalind S. Helderman contributed to this report.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0094"><line>Rep. Jeff Morris, an Anacortes Democrat on the transportation committee, said inattentive driving is already an infraction.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>But there is plenty of evidence that cell phone use is a major distraction.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>New York, New Jersey, and Washington, D.C., among others, have banned the use of hand-held sets while driving.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>Next time, make paying the driver the last thing you do.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>&quot;There was no reason for him to go off (the ramp) other than he just took it too fast, and that was because he was distracted by the cell phone,&quot; said Eric Houston, the Overland Park police officer who investigated the crash last summer.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>Rader disputed the industry's assertion that cell phones shouldn't be singled out as a problem.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0173"><line>But their use should be banned for motorists while in motion.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>As the 17-year-old driver exited U.S. 69 in Overland Park, he rolled his pickup as he tried to grab a ringing cell phone from the passenger-side floorboard, police said.</line><line>A 15-year-old girl, driving without her permit at 1 a.m., struck a parked Jeep when she reached to the passenger seat to answer a phone.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0173"><line>Last year, Connecticut and the city of Chicago joined New York state, New Jersey, and Washington, D.C., in banning the use of hand-held phones by motorists.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>&quot;There are language issues.</line><line>Perhaps.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>&quot;If someone wants to go to that degree, at the same time, we'd have to look at banning all those distractive behaviors, to be fair.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0094"><line>&quot;I'm going to come back with it next year,&quot; she said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>&quot;The body of evidence is pointing toward the conversation as being a major distraction when driving and talking on the cell phone.&quot;<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="49"/></line><line>&quot;In our mind, it's still a tossup whether hands-free or handheld (prohibitions would help).&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>&quot;When you're talking, you focus more on the conversation than the road,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>&quot;What this research will do is add to the body of evidence that both hands-free and handheld phones pose a risk while driving,&quot; said Russ Rader, a spokesman for the institute, which is funded by auto insurers.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>That Massachusetts drivers rank ahead of only those in Mississippi in wearing seat belts is an embarrassment, but says much about our attitudes about driving.</line><line>To do the wrong thing three times in a row is just plain stupid.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>And it underscores how completely, and in such a short time, the device has come to dominate people's lives.</line><line>Taking eyes off the road was second -- and the longer the eyes were away, the more likely a crash.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>CTIA could not comment on that claim.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050806.0640"><line>Sundeen said it is more difficult to prosecute such cases, unlike drunken driving or failure to use a seat belt where there is often clear evidence.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="38,5,8"><scu uid="28" label="Enforcement is difficult." weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>At least 25 state legislatures are considering restrictions on cell phone use while driving, many aimed at young drivers.</line><line>Last year, Maryland legislators prohibited drivers younger than 18 from using any cell phone.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0071"><line>Brooks City-Base, on city-owned land, is not considering one, a base spokesman said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>But forget the cash?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>And evidence is mounting that using a hands-free device instead of a hand-held phone while behind the wheel does little to improve safety, and may even give drivers a false sense of security.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="3,35"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>&quot;The cell phone has just been the poster child.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>He said &quot;I'm sorry&quot; when informed that Max was in the car, but did not seem especially contrite.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>The so-called automatic enforcement technology photographs the license plates of cars as they are going through red lights, and civil citations are mailed to violators.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0071"><line>&quot;Right now, we are pulling people over,&quot; often to find they aren't aware of the rule, he said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0173"><line>It is not a matter of personal freedom when distracted drivers endanger others' lives and limbs, or even when they bang a few thousand fenders, driving up everyone's insurance premiums.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>Garcia compares the public attitude about the D.C. law to the initial reaction to seat-belt laws -- first came resistance and a minimum of enforcement, then crash data and public awareness campaigns gradually prompted the public to buckle up.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="5"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0071"><line>Highway Traffic Safety Administration that found cell phone use was a growing cause of accidents.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="13,43"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050806.0640"><line>Beginning Monday, Colorado is banning young drivers from talking on cellular phones while they're behind the wheel _ a small step more states are taking in hopes of promoting safety without upsetting voters who can't live without the convenience.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="29"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>They said their legislatures appeared to be in no mood to place new curbs on personal freedoms.</line><line>Cell phones and teens are becoming an increasingly dangerous combination on the highway, traffic-safety advocates say.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0094"><line>She's been pushing the bill in Olympia for the past seven years.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>Last year Kansas recorded 260 crashes in which a cell phone was a contributing factor.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>&quot;The problem with the laws that are being passed is they are leaving people with the impression that hands-free phones are safer and they're clearly not,&quot; Rader said.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="36"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>He may forget an open door.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>Put down the cellphone.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>The lack of compliance is common talk in the city.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="0"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>On one level, it is hard not to sympathize with the drivers.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>There are no such limits in Kansas and Missouri.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="29"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>California still has no such laws banning cell phones for drivers -- although one law prohibits bus drivers from talking while behind the wheel.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="6" sums="11,22,32,37,42,5"><scu uid="30" label="Bus drivers are being banned from using cell phones." weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0071"><line>Lackland is the first Air Force base in Texas' Bexar County to enforce a ban on use of cell phones while driving, a rule that's becoming common on military bases under a Pentagon directive.</line><line>The same penalty would apply if they are caught six times in two years, said Master Sgt. Aaron Thieken.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="29"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>She took out the frame.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0173"><line>(One in a series of editorials about America's car culture.)</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>In Massachusetts, drivers can be ticketed only if they have been stopped for another offense.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0094"><line>The House wrote a neutered version that prohibits driving and talking on a cell phone for only people who have an instruction permit or an intermediate driver's license given to someone under age 18.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>The technology is not popular with the live-free-or-die crowd, but civil citations have been widely upheld by the courts.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>&quot;We know that when you're learning a skill, you should not be distracted while you are doing it,&quot; said Mark Rosenker, acting chairman of the safety board.</line><line>&quot;When you add something to the mix on top of their inexperience, it only equates to more crashes with injuries and fatalities.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>Daus' sense is that the situation has improved of late.</line><line>Indeed, the passenger may as well not exist.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>Everyone complains about Massachusetts' high automobile insurance rates.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="23"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>&quot;I don't feel very safe driving right now, because I'm a beginning driver,&quot; she said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>But an argument is growing that laws requiring hands-free devices might contribute to hazards by encouraging drivers to talk longer.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line><line>In the year and a half since Washington D.C. began restricting drivers' cell phone use, police say they have issued thousands of tickets to violators.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="14"><scu uid="28" label="Enforcement is difficult." weight="3"/></annotation></line><line>The automobile group AAA agrees, urging drivers to use cell phones only in emergencies and saying the rush to enact new laws is &quot;probably sending the wrong message,&quot; said spokesman Mantill Williams.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="20,42"><scu uid="37" label="Driver education is a large part of cell-phone law enforcement" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>In response, 15 states and the District of Columbia have passed legislation allowing cities and towns to use video cameras to ticket violators.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>He may forget the baby.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050806.0640"><line>So far, only New York, New Jersey, the District of Columbia and Connecticut prohibit the use of hand-held phones while driving, though other states have adopted limited restrictions for young drivers or school bus drivers.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="13,40,43"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>This January, 370 tickets were issued, he said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>The new push in the Legislature to require drivers to wear seat belts is a good place to start.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0173"><line>Motorists using cellphones are four times as likely to be in an accident as those who aren't, according to a study last year in Australia.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>The study examined the cell-phone records of crash victims interviewed in emergency rooms between April 2002 and July 2004.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>New York, New Jersey, Connecticut and Washington D.C. have the most restrictive laws, according to the National Conference of State Legislatures.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0071"><line>Though the post commander could ban a repeat violator from driving there, no one has yet lost driving privileges.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>It tends to encourage being pretty passive.&quot;</line><line>A shocking story?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>The list goes on and on.&quot;<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line><line>&quot;I don't want to get into a wreck,&quot; she said.</line><line>He said young drivers must recognize that the distraction is just the start of what can go wrong.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0173"><line>Cellphones are great for emergencies; a driver can pull over and dial 911.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051205.0960"><line>The law takes effect Jan. 2.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="12,6"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>They also do not understand why young people should be singled out when wireless phones are as much of a distraction to adults.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0094"><line>Rep. Ed Murray, chairman of the House Transportation Committee, said gutting it was the only way to get the bill through his committee.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>&quot;The real issue is driving while distracted,&quot; Ramsey said.</line><line>Many say they spot police officers violating the law.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>Despite the moaning about them that you hear from some New Yorkers, they usually know their way around, at least in Manhattan, and they sometimes endure more abuse than they deserve.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>&quot;It's just like speeding,&quot; she said.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0173"><line>Colorado, Delaware, Maryland, and Tennessee barred their use by young drivers.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>That being the case, I had a suggestion for Max's mom.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>It found a consistent fourfold increased risk of injury among drivers on cell phones -- be they men or women, older or younger drivers.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0071"><line>The Defense Department approved restrictions on cell phone use for motorists last year, leaving the military services and individual bases to decide when and how to enforce the rules.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051205.0960"><line>The law allows the use of hands-free mobile phone devices while driving and hand-held phones during emergencies.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="19,44,49"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>The Kansas City Star</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>The powerful cellphone industry, with much to lose, is the biggest obstacle to regulation.</line><line>Steve Bailey is a Globe columnist.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>The woman, who was 26 weeks pregnant, complained of back and neck pain after the September 2004 crash in Overland Park.</line><line>But police reports are laced with examples of how teens wreck when they turn their attentions to cell phones.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>Theirs is a lonely job.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>&quot;The bottom line is that people should not be talking on cell phones while they're driving.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>&quot;You can get into an argument, or offend somebody,&quot; Schaller said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>It's a distraction that lasts a period of minutes.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>They can become so distracted that they miss a turn or fail to stop.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>Fifteen-year-old Kaitlyn Tompkins, for one, is nervous about doing anything besides focusing on the road.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>&quot;Obviously, if you're dialing a cell phone, you're going to take your eyes off the road longer than if you're popping a CD in,&quot; said Sherry Box, spokeswoman for the Transportation Institute.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0173"><line>But that must change.</line><line>Far too often, 911 is being called because someone was on a cellphone.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>And that was that.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>A federal study found that last year 8 percent of all U.S. motorists, or about 1.2 million drivers, used cell phones while operating their vehicles at any given time.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="19,48"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>One in three drivers said their greatest aggravation on the road is cell-phone use by other drivers, according to one of the recent studies.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>The recommendation by the National Transportation Safety Board comes at a time when people of all ages are using cell phones more frequently while on the road.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="19"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>&quot;The only reason it would end up in a report is if the insured indicates the crash was due to the cell phone, and we very rarely include it in our reports,&quot; said Olya Mikhailova of Georgetown Insurance Group.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0071"><line>&quot;All you have to do is pull over&quot; to talk on a cell phone, he added.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>&quot;We know it's still happening out there.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>Marshall said the department is still weighing whether prohibitions would help.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>Here's what happened:</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0173"><line>Next: Real auto insurance reform</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>But at what cost?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>&quot;It's difficult for officers to readily ascertain the age of the driver, and it's difficult to determine if the driver is using a hands-free phone.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051205.0960"><line>The U.S. Caribbean territory of 110,000 residents is the only part of the U.S. where people drive on the left, a colonial relic from when the territory was owned by Denmark.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050806.0640"><line>The Colorado law affects teens with restricted licenses _ brand-new drivers who must have an adult drive with them for a year.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="44"><scu uid="31" label="Cell phone use by young drivers is banned in some places." weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0173"><line>Among drivers 16 to 24 years old, frighteningly, it was up to 10 percent.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>Every state has at some point considered legislation on cell phones behind the wheel, while a few states have banned phones unless they're hands-free devices, according to the National Conference of State Legislatures.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>The sky was clear.</line><line>Authorities said they doubted that statistics fully measured the problem, because most drivers did not readily admit they were talking on a cell phone before a crash.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0094"><line>Others said using a hands-free device wouldn't be less distracting than just gabbing on the cell phone.</line><line>She said constituents are tired of seeing people chatting on their cell phones when they should have both hands on the wheel.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>Harvard University's Center for Risk Analysis estimated 2,600 people are killed and 330,000 injured a year because of drivers talking on their cellphones - and that was three years ago.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0071"><line>(E-mail: shuddleston(a)express-news.net)</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>They are all too familiar with drivers who hurtle through the streets while talking into the microphone of a hidden cellphone, usually in a language incomprehensible to the passenger.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>Mayor Anthony A. Williams, D, says the police department &quot;is doing a very good job of striking a balance between zealous enforcement and educating drivers.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>Traffic was routine for a weekday afternoon.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0071"><line>Reidinger said the rule has generally been well-received -- even though it bars motorists from using cell phones altogether while driving.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>&quot;They don't know how to handle it once they get to a problem,&quot; Ricks said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0173"><line>But the United States is only catching up with global trends.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>It is obvious whether you have been nearly rear-ended by the fool gabbing on his cellphone in the next car or done it yourself.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0173"><line>It is time for Massachusetts to put a stop to the practice.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>Talking on your cellphone while driving is a bad idea.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="10,18"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>The number of cell phone-related summonses issued in 2005 was well below the 2004 total, a fact that he attributed to better compliance, not laxer enforcement.</line><line>Mom, her heart pounding, went on her way with the baby.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>They should not be talking on cell phones of any kind while they're driving.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>Now the National Transportation Safety Board is urging other states to pass similar laws for teens learning to drive.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="4" sums="10,32,36,44"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>Buckle up or pay up.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>&quot;I don't really think it distracts me,&quot; T.C. Alex, a 15-year-old from Olathe, said.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>Used at problem intersections, cameras are a powerful and cost-effective deterrent to impatient drivers.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>Then she got out to retrieve the stroller frame.</line><line>The cabby popped the trunk.</line><line>But &quot;of course, from a safety angle, we're not for cell phone use while driving,&quot; said William Lindauer, a member of the alliance's organizing committee.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>If it can wait, let it wait.&quot;<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>And every year we get to pay for it come premium time.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="55"/></line><line>Twenty-two states and the District of Columbia allow the police to stop drivers solely for not wearing a seat belt.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>That's when the driver took off with (1) his rear right door open, and, more important, (2) the baby still in the back seat.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>Teens already account for a disproportionate share of traffic fatalities, and wireless phones exacerbate the problem, they say.</line><line>Capt. Chris Ricks of the Missouri Highway Patrol said education, not necessarily more laws, is the answer.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="57"><scu uid="37" label="Driver education is a large part of cell-phone law enforcement" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>Sometimes things get busy.&quot;</line><line>In another recent study, the Virginia Tech Transportation Institute found that fatigue was the most frequent cause of accidents.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050806.0640"><line>Most states are looking at limited bans because it is unclear _ and a bone of contention with the telecommunications industry _ whether cell phone use while driving can be tied to more accidents.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="22"><scu uid="26" label="States have tried to pass restrictive cellphone/driving legislation" weight="3"/><scu uid="36" label="The percentage of accidents caused by cell phone use is low." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>The rapid proliferation of cell phones -- last week it was reported that cell phones have overtaken land lines in the United States and that nearly half of all drivers use them behind the wheel -- has increasingly been a source of tension on the road.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>On radio talk shows, callers often complain about drivers weaving down streets with cell phones stuck to their ears.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>Drivers using cellphones are four times as likely to get into crashes serious enough to send them to the hospital, according to the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0094"><line>He said he didn't want to target just cell phones since global positioning devices and other electronics are just as distracting.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>One-third of the drivers said their calls had been made on handheld phones, the study said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>A recent follow-up survey showed the reduction has held steady, he said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0173"><line>Truckers honk when they stray from their lanes.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>His mind was everywhere except where it was supposed to be: on his work.</line><line>So far, so good.</line><line>Fair enough.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0173"><line>Everyone has personal stories of accidents or near misses, but studies are now coming in that make it clear: Cellphone use by drivers in motion is a menace, and a growing one.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>New drivers are dialing for danger</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>Even the drivers' union, the New York Taxi Workers Alliance, does not defend such behavior.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>Let's look at banning drive-through restaurants.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>And our own compulsive behavior.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050806.0640"><line>He said many lawmakers oppose stronger laws because they don't want to anger their constituents.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>Many of us have.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0094"><line>&quot;I was one of the only votes&quot; for Eide's original bill, said Murray, a Democrat from Seattle.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>&quot;The biggest concern for young drivers is their lack of experience,&quot; said Lt. John Eickhorn of the Kansas Highway Patrol.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>It is no secret why we have some of the highest rates in the country: Massachusetts leads the nation in accidents - 40 percent higher than the state with the second-highest rate, Rhode Island.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>Oh, did I mention that the driver was yakking away on his cell phone?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>&quot;If you single one possible distraction out, you could be doing a disservice by creating a false sense of security that you've taken care of the potential problem,&quot; said John Walls, spokesman for CTIA-the Wireless Association.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>&quot;It sounds good, and politicians love it because it makes it sound like they're doing something.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>&quot;I get distracted enough by the radio.&quot;<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>And might they not be a bit less lonely if they just tried talking to their passengers, who always have the right to say they would rather ride in silence?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>&quot;Anything that takes away from the total focus of learning how to drive is a distraction,&quot; he said.</line><line>Consider these:</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0071"><line>If you drive on Lackland Air Force Base, it's time to turn off your cell phone -- or risk being grounded.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="11,14"><scu uid="29" label="Cell phone use while driving is being banned on military bases" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>It's not a safety device; it's just a convenience device.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>There is plenty we could do that would make driving safer and lower rates - though it sometimes involves surrendering a piece of our cherished &quot;personal freedoms.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>She caught up with the cab after half a block.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>Brian McKearney, 15, said he was aware of the risk.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>And Russ Rader, spokesman for the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety, said he is not aware of any studies looking at the city law's effect on safety.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="43"><scu uid="27" label="Effectiveness is difficult to assess." weight="2"/></annotation></line><line>Linda Garcia, director of the communications, culture and technology program at Georgetown University, said the cell phone lends itself to &quot;multitasking,&quot; often the goal of area workaholics, but at a price.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051205.0960"><line>&quot;We've talked to (paramedics) who've said there have been so many accidents from people on cell phones yapping away,&quot; said Sen. Roosevelt David, the law's author, who acknowledged almost hitting another car while using his mobile phone behind the wheel.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="20,21"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>But it could also be risky.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>The Senate killed a bill this session to require hands-free phones for all drivers.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>But there is a good reason cabbies are forbidden to talk on cell phones, even with hands-free devices, while they are in motion.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="13,43"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0071"><line>The base began stopping cars and giving verbal warnings Feb. 27.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>Ramsey said local drivers are starting to comply more, in part because ear devices have become &quot;cool, almost a status thing.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0071"><line>&quot;That's what I do.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>The wireless phone industry supports efforts to improve highway safety but believes they should focus on all potential distractions.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>But the national wireless association says cell phones shouldn't be singled out without considering all the distractions drivers experience while in their vehicles -- the burgers, the coffee, the kids who need attention.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>&quot;The numbers bear that out -- if they see it, they write it,&quot; Ramsey said in a recent interview.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>In that age group, cell-phone-related crashes rose 12 percent last year in Missouri and 38 percent in Kansas.</line><line>I'm looking out my mirror and that kind of thing,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>As a precaution, to signal that she wasn't finished, she left her door open.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>On his monthly call-in show, D.C. Police Chief Charles Ramsey is often challenged about his commitment to enforcing it.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0071"><line>Unlike a cell phone ban initiated in October at Fort Sam Houston, an Army post, the new rule at Lackland permits the use of hands-free cell phone devices with a single earpiece.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="21"><scu uid="29" label="Cell phone use while driving is being banned on military bases" weight="4"/><scu uid="38" label="Enforcement policies vary by military base" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>&quot;But we don't have our heads in the sand,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>Drivers using cell phones -- even hands-free models -- are four times more likely to get into a serious injury crash, according to a study being released today.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="14,55"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>Cell phone users in the United States have increased from 34 million a decade ago to more than 203 million, according to CTIA -- the Wireless Association, and the debate about the technological phenomenon has only begun.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>She said she thought it made sense to restrict phones for inexperienced drivers.</line><line>No injuries were reported.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>Not a chance.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0173"><line>Some 40 countries, including most of Europe, restrict cellphone use by drivers.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="23"><scu uid="33" label="Some places prohibit use of hand-held phones while driving." weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>On reaching her destination, she paid the driver.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>Several local insurance offices said the issue rarely comes up.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>According to the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, seat belt usage in Massachusetts stands at 64.8 percent, compared to 82 percent nationwide.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>It may complain that fines imposed by the city's Taxi and Limousine Commission are too high.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>An 18-year-old man struck a car driven by a pregnant woman as he reached to grab a cell phone from his back pants pocket.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>Drivers work hard.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>Fifteen-year-old Callie Wheeler said she sometimes answered the phone while she was driving but talked only briefly.</line><line>The girl said she panicked, hitting the gas pedal instead of the brakes.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>This year, a Virginia bill that would prohibit 16- and 17-years-olds from talking on the phone while driving passed the state Senate but was killed in a House subcommittee.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="10"><scu uid="31" label="Cell phone use by young drivers is banned in some places." weight="4"/><scu uid="26" label="States have tried to pass restrictive cellphone/driving legislation" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>A new mother -- OK, she's my daughter, but that is not the point of this tale -- watched disbelievingly the other day as a New York cabby drove away with her baby boy.</line><line>But New Yorkers who take taxis even semiregularly will not be surprised.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>(Correction: New Hampshire, of course, has no adult seat belt law at all.)</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0071"><line>Supervisors and commanders are notified when government or military personnel are cited.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050806.0640"><line>The cell phone industry says studies show cell phone use was a factor in less than 1 percent of all accidents in the six states that require reporting.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="33,40"><scu uid="36" label="The percentage of accidents caused by cell phone use is low." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>Maggie, yelling &quot;Hey!&quot; gave chase.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0031"><line>&quot;It's not a moment, a distraction of changing the radio station or talking to your child in the back seat.</line><line>&quot;We have often made the argument that it's the conversation, and perhaps dialing the phone, that are the distractions,&quot; said Tom Marshall, a spokesman for the California Highway Patrol.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050806.0640"><line>Police can issue a citation only if the driver is stopped for another violation.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0173"><line>Even so, the number of drivers using a cellphone at any given time rose from 5 to 6 percent nationally between 2004 and 2005, according to a report last month from the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060302.0094"><line>Some said it was another case of big government.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060218.0153"><line>Mom hailed the taxi, with 4-month-old Max in his stroller, one of those models with an upper part that lifts up and doubles as a car seat.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>The pavement was dry.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050806.0640"><line>States are willing to take &quot;baby steps&quot; with younger drivers because it's easier to get the legislation passed, Sundeen said.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="11,41,55"><scu uid="35" label="Cell phone laws regarding young people or school bus drivers are more likely to pass and maintain constituent support." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>In Missouri, about 31 percent of the 1,246 cell-phone related crashes in 2004 involved a driver younger than 21.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>Reaction to D.C.'s law -- one of the first in the country -- shows how ambivalent the public is about having anything, even safety, interfere with the beloved cell phone.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050806.0640"><line>This year, 38 states tried to pass legislation restricting cell phones, most focusing on younger drivers and driving while distracted.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="3" sums="21,37,40"><scu uid="26" label="States have tried to pass restrictive cellphone/driving legislation" weight="3"/><scu uid="35" label="Cell phone laws regarding young people or school bus drivers are more likely to pass and maintain constituent support." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060302.0147"><line>And Ramsey urged people to report any officers they see breaking the law.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="32"><scu uid="28" label="Enforcement is difficult." weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051111.0234"><line>&quot;Enforcement is a big problem,&quot; said Russ Rader, a spokesman for the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety, a research organization that is funded by auto insurers.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0173"><line>Representative James Marzilli, an Arlington Democrat who is pushing for an outright ban of all devices, says he fears that the lack of restrictions has given drivers a sense that the use of cellphones &quot;is a birthright - like cars themselves.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060104.0080"><line>If the answer is none of the above, then stop complaining and send in your insurance premium.</line></document></collection>